SIMPLE: effect
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Effect
<hw>Ef*fect"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>effectus</ets>, fr. <ets>efficere</ets>, <ets>effectum</ets>, to
effect; <ets>ex</ets> + <ets>facere</ets> to make: cf. F.
<ets>effet</ets>, formerly also spelled <ets>effect</ets>. See
<er>Fact</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Execution; performance;
realization; operation; <as>as, the law goes into <ex>effect</ex> in
May</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That no compunctious visitings of nature⟦br⟧
Shake my fell purpose, nor keep peace between⟦br⟧
The <qex>effect</qex> and it.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Manifestation; expression; sign.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the large <qex>effects</qex>⟦br⟧
That troop with majesty.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In general: That which is produced by an agent or
cause; the event which follows immediately from an antecedent, called
the <xex>cause</xex>; result; consequence; outcome; fruit; <as>as, the
<ex>effect</ex> of luxury</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>effect</qex> is the unfailing index of the amount of the
cause.</q> <rj><qau>Whewell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Impression left on the mind; sensation
produced.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Patchwork . . . introduced for oratorical <qex>effect</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>J. C. Shairp.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>effect</qex> was heightened by the wild and lonely nature
of the place.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Power to produce results; efficiency; force;
importance; account; <as>as, to speak with
<ex>effect</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Consequence intended; purpose; meaning; general
intent; -- with <xex>to</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They spake to her to that <qex>effect</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>2 Chron.
xxxiv. 22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The purport; the sum and substance.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>effect</xex> of his intent.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj></p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Reality; actual meaning; fact, as distinguished from
mere appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No other in <qex>effect</qex> than what it seems.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Goods; movables; personal estate;
-- sometimes used to embrace real as well as personal property; <as>as,
the people escaped from the town with their
<ex>effects</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>For effect</b></col>, <cd>for an exaggerated impression
or excitement.</cd> -- <col><b>In effect</b></col>, <cd>in fact; in
substance. See 8, above.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Of no effect</b></col>,
<col><b>Of none effect</b></col>, <col><b>To no effect</b></col>,
<it>or</it> <col><b>Without effect</b></col></mcol>, <cd>destitute of
results, validity, force, and the like; vain; fruitless.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧Making the word of God <xex>of none effect</xex> through your
tradition.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Mark vii. 13.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧All my study be <xex>to
no effect</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To give effect
to</b></col>, <cd>to make valid; to carry out in practice; to push to
its results.</cd> -- <col><b>To take effect</b></col>, <cd>to become
operative, to accomplish aims.</cd> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj> </cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Effect</er>, <er>Consequence</er>,
<er>Result</er>.</syn> <usage>These words indicate things which arise
out of some antecedent, or follow as a consequent. <xex>Effect</xex>,
which may be regarded as the generic term, denotes that which springs
directly from something which can properly be termed a cause. A
<xex>consequence</xex> is more remote, not being strictly caused, nor
yet a mere sequence, but following out of and following indirectly, or
in the train of events, something on which it truly depends. A
<xex>result</xex> is still more remote and variable, like the rebound of
an elastic body which falls in very different directions. We may foresee
the <xex>effects</xex> of a measure, may conjecture its
<xex>consequences</xex>, but can rarely discover its final
<xex>results</xex>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Resolving all events, with their <qex>effects</qex>⟦br⟧
And manifold <qex>results</qex>, into the will⟦br⟧
And arbitration wise of the Supreme.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shun the bitter <qex>consequence</qex>, for know,⟦br⟧
The day thou eatest thereof, . . . thou shalt die.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Effect</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Effect
<hw>Ef*fect"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Effected</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Effecting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To produce, as a
cause or agent; to cause to be.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So great a body such exploits to <qex>effect</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bring to pass; to execute; to enforce; to
achieve; to accomplish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>effect</qex> that which the divine counsels had
decreed.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hurd.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They sailed away without <qex>effecting</qex> their purpose.</q>
<rj><qau>Jowett (Th. ).</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To accomplish; fulfill; achieve; complete;
execute; perform; attain. See <er>Accomplish</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Effecter</ent>⟦br⟧
